\pard\keep\keepn\s1\sb120\sl276\slmult1\cf1\b\i0\f0\fs28 What Is \i Cthulhu Eternal?\i0\f1\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\b0\i\fs22 Cthulhu Eternal\i0  is a tabletop roleplaying game which allows you to play out a broad range of investigative adventures in different eras of history, as tainted by the ravages of H.P. Lovecraft\rquote s Cthulhu Mythos. \par
The only assumptions made by the \i Cthulhu Eternal\i0  rules are that:\par
\pard\fi-360\li765\sa200\sl276\slmult1\f2\'b7\tab\f1 The game takes place in an era of our planet\rquote s past, present, or future where humanity is the prevailing \endash  although not necessarily only \endash  species actively shaping the world.\par
\f2\'b7\tab\f1 The world is haunted by secret and mysterious survivals of otherworldly or extra-dimensional forces of Lovecraft\rquote s mythos; clues to their existence are scattered through written accounts (if such exist) or folktales passed from generation-to-generation.\par
\f2\'b7\tab\f1 Players take on roles of everyday people from the era, without special pulp-like \ldblquote super-powers\rdblquote ; regardless of their frailty they pursue the truth about the Cthulhu Mythos and ultimately work to thwart its corrosive influence.\par
\f2\'b7\tab\f1 Player characters are physical human beings that can be hurt, fall unconscious, or die if subject to physical damage \endash  and conversely, they can be healed using whatever knowledge of \ldblquote first aid\rdblquote  exists in the historical era.\par
\f2\'b7\tab\f1 Player characters are conscious and intelligent beings whose sanity can be adversely affected by witnessing terrible things beyond normal human comprehension \endash  and conversely, they can have their mental state made better by whatever folk-remedies or medical science exists in the historical era.\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\qc\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s1\sb480\sl276\slmult1\cf1\b\f0\fs28 Lovecraftian Investigations in the Jazz Age\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\b0\f1\fs22 This version of Cthulhu Eternal is specifically tailored to support Lovecraftian games set in the Jazz Age \endash  that is, the world as it was in the early 20\super th\nosupersub  Century (between the World Wars). This is an attractive option for a game setting \endash  and one that has been used many times \endash  for one simple reason. When H.P. Lovecraft was writing his uncanny tales of weird horror, he frequently chose to set them in the world that was most familiar to him and his readers: the present-day world at the time they were written. Given that those tales were penned between 1920 and Lovecraft\rquote s death in 1937, there are plenty of examples of original creations that take place in the inter-war era we\rquote ve termed the \ldblquote Jazz Age.\rdblquote  Those stories can easily serve as great sources of inspiration for your own scenarios \endash  and best of all they are reliably authentic to the period (because they were written by someone living through it).\par
While Lovecraft set the ball rolling on the style of weird tale we now call \ldblquote Lovecraftian\rdblquote  he was certainly not the only person who was writing contemporary horror fiction in the 1920s and 1930s with a \ldblquote cosmic\rdblquote  flavor. In fact, Lovecraft himself famously encouraged friends and correspondents to join in with his grand game of inventing this nascent sub-genre, sometimes suggesting ideas to colleagues, sometimes revising their fiction for pay. This means that there are other authors of the period whose fiction can serve as inspiration for era-authentic games. Because each writer has his or her own unique voice, tracking down works by some of these contemporaries of H.P. Lovecraft can give you a different style of \ldblquote Mythos\rdblquote  story that you can use as a starting point for your own ideas. Some writers you can search out:\par
\pard\fi-360\li720\sa200\sl276\slmult1\f2\'b7\tab\f1 Frank Belknap Long\par
\f2\'b7\tab\f1 Robert Bloch\par
\f2\'b7\tab\f1 Robert E. Howard\par
\f2\'b7\tab\f1 Henry Kuttner\par
\f2\'b7\tab\f1 Manly Wade Wellman\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1 Of course, there is no reason that you need to limit yourself to creating scenarios and plots inspired by those writing contemporary fiction in the 1920s or 1930s. Indeed, you can ignore those writers entirely and focus on weaving your original ideas into a compelling Jazz Age scenario or campaign. There are, however, a few pitfalls that you should try to avoid when striking out on your own:\par
\pard\fi-360\li1080\sa200\sl276\slmult1 1.\tab Social structures in the Jazz Age are typically quite different to anything we\rquote ve personally experienced,\par
2.\tab The technology of the 1920s and 1930s is simplistic by our standards (and it\rquote s easy to make assumptions that are anachronistic),\par
3.\tab People in the Jazz Age typically knew much less about the current state of the world outside their immediate vicinity: there is no instant communication of news. Indeed, there still exist some corners of the world which have not been fully explored and documented.\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1 In general, it is worth investing some time in navigating these pitfalls since a story that ignores major differences in society, technology, etc., will not feel especially genuine to the period. Depending on your players, this can spoil any chance of them feeling immersed in the unique \ldblquote feel\rdblquote  of the era. It\rquote s not just about avoiding blatant anachronisms (\ldblquote yes some cops used radios to keep in contact, but there were no portable hand-held radios that could be used away from patrol cars\rdblquote ). It\rquote s also about representing society in a believable fashion. How did people really live their lives in the era? How did the gadgets of the age support their life, and how did the limitations of technology impact of the lives of the average person?\par
The best way to make your Jazz Age games feel authentic is to do a little bit of research about the historical era before you dive headlong into creating your Mythos masterpiece. Calling it \ldblquote research\rdblquote  makes it seem like it\rquote s necessarily boring \endash  hitting the library (real or online) and diving into social histories of the inter-war period. If that\rquote s your bag, there are a lot of great resources that will reward your investment of time. But it\rquote s just as possible that your research might seek to learn details of the Jazz Age through movies or TV series set in the era. A few great examples of the latter category include:\par
\pard\fi-360\li720\sa200\sl276\slmult1\f2\'b7\tab\i\f1 Boardwalk Empire\i0  (TV Series, 2010\emdash 2014).\par
\f2\'b7\tab\i\f1 Carniv\'e0le\i0  (TV Series, 2003\emdash 2005).\par
\f2\'b7\tab\i\f1 Peaky Blinders\i0  (TV Series, 2013\emdash 2022).\par
\f2\'b7\tab\i\f1 Miller\rquote s Crossing\i0  (Coen Brothers Movie, 1990).\par
\f2\'b7\tab\i\f1 Something Wicked This Way Comes\i0  (1984 Dark Fantasy Movie).\par
\f2\'b7\tab\i\f1 Horror Express\i0  (1972 Movie with Christopher Lee, Peter Cushing and Telly Savalas; not technically set in the Jazz Age but close enough).\par
\f2\'b7\tab\i\f1 The Great Gatsby\i0  (the F. Scott Fitzgerald novel, or one of its several movie versions including the visually lavish 2013 Baz Luhrmann production).\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1 Naturally, when you\rquote re taking inspiration from non-horror fiction or media to build a compelling backdrop for your original horrific tale, the key to success is finding the right balance between period color and weird horror. Having lots of period detail is great, but an entire game which features nothing but gangsters and bootleggers will quickly bore a group that has turned up to your table expecting a weird fiction tale. Conversely, a game which is strong on \ldblquote established Mythos-continuity\rdblquote  but which feels like it\rquote s just a modern-day story with the serial number filed off and replaced with 1920s clich\'e9s, will come off as arbitrary. After all, if it makes no difference whether the tale is set in the Jazz Age or modern-day why should players go to the effort of getting into the right \ldblquote mood\rdblquote  for this unique setting? \par
As with everything the key is balance and adapting to what players will find most fun. As long as you listen to what your players say they want out of a game experience \endash  you will never fail when it comes to bringing a compelling investigative horror game alive at the table.\par
