\pard\keep\keepn\s1\sl276\slmult1\f0 PART I: RULES OF THE GAME\par
\pard\sa120\sl276\slmult1\cf0\b0\f1\fs22 This section describes the rules that all players will need to know to play a game of \i Cthulhu Eternal\i0 . It describes:\par
\pard\fi-360\li720\sa200\sl276\slmult1\f2\'b7\tab\f1 How to \b create characters\b0  whose roles players will adopt in the shared Lovecraftian stories;\par
\f2\'b7\tab\f1 How characters make use of their \b skills and attributes\b0  to try to overcome challenges they encounter;\par
\f2\'b7\tab\f1 How \b combat\b0  works, when things turn violent;\par
\f2\'b7\tab\f1 How the fragile \b sanity\b0  of each player\rquote s character may become eroded by encounters with horrors, both mundane and unnatural;\par
\pard\fi-357\li714\sa120\sl276\slmult1\f2\'b7\tab\f1 What player characters can do during the quiet \b downtime\b0  between perilous adventures against unnatural entities.\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s1\fi-431\li431\sl276\slmult1\cf1\b\f0\fs28 1.0\tab Core Game Concepts\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\b0\f1\fs22 These rules tell you everything you need to know in order to play \i Cthulhu Eternal\f3 .\par
\i0\f1 As with most tabletop roleplaying games, when playing \i Cthulhu Eternal\i0  one player takes on the responsibility of setting the scene and narrating the events which make up a \i Cthulhu Eternal \i0 adventure. That individual is termed the \b Game Moderator\b0 . All other players take on the roles of individual every-day people from an era of human history who are swept up in investigating the Cthulhu Mythos. These characters are called \b Protagonists\b0  (with the term capitalized for clarity). Protagonists will encounter a multitude of other characters whose roles are \i not\i0  being played by other players \endash  those characters are called \b Non-Player Characters\b0  (or NPCs) and their actions are controlled by the Game Moderator.\par
In this book you\rquote ll find rules for creating Protagonists and a full set of rules for running adventures in a Lovecraftian world of your group\rquote s choosing or devising.\par
In addition to this book, you also need pencils to record changes to your character sheet, scratch paper to draw sketches and take notes, and dice.\par
\i Cthulhu Eternal\f3  \i0\f1 uses polyhedral dice common to tabletop role-playing games: four-sided, six-sided, eight-sided, ten-sided, twelve-sided, and twenty-sided. The game plays best when you have a few of each on the table. Or you can find automated dice rollers on the Web and as mobile apps.\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s2\fi-576\li576\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0\fs26 1.1\tab Rolling the Dice\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\b0\f1\fs22 When the rules need you to roll dice, they use a particular nomenclature to save time and space: \ldblquote #D#,\rdblquote  as in \ldblquote 1D8\rdblquote  or \ldblquote 4D6.\rdblquote  The first number is the number of dice. The \ldblquote D\rdblquote  stands for \ldblquote dice with the following number of sides.\rdblquote  The second number is the number of faces on the die. \ldblquote 1D8\rdblquote  means roll one eight-sided die. \ldblquote 4D6\rdblquote  means roll four six-sided dice and add the numbers together. Sometimes you add or subtract a number from the roll. If it says \ldblquote 1D6+2,\rdblquote  that means roll one six-sided die and add two to the result.\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s2\fi-576\li576\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0\fs26 1.2\tab Percentile Dice (\ldblquote 1D100\rdblquote )\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\b0\f1\fs22 Actions in \i Cthulhu Eternal\f3  \i0\f1 are resolved using \b percentile dice.\b0  That means you roll two ten-sided dice to get a number from 1 to 100. To do this, you don\rquote t add the individual die values together but instead treat each number as a digit (0\emdash 9). Before you make the roll, designate one die as the tens digit and the other as the ones digit. A zero (0) on the tens die counts as zero except when the ones die is also 0; then the 0 on the tens die counts as 10. For example:\par
\pard\fi-360\li720\sa200\sl276\slmult1\f2\'b7\tab\f1 The tens die comes up \ldblquote 0\rdblquote  and the ones die comes up \ldblquote 3\rdblquote : 03, or 3.\par
\f2\'b7\tab\f1 The tens die comes up \ldblquote 3\rdblquote  and the ones die comes up \ldblquote 0\rdblquote : 30.\par
\f2\'b7\tab\f1 Both dice come up \ldblquote 0\rdblquote : 100.\par
\f2\'b7\tab\f1 The tens die comes up \ldblquote 6\rdblquote  and the ones die comes up \ldblquote 2\rdblquote : 62.\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s1\fi-432\li432\sb120\sl276\slmult1\cf1\b\f0\fs28 2.0\tab Protagonists\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\b0\f1\fs22 Your Protagonist represents the fictional persona that you will control in the game. You will spend a lot of time navigating your Protagonist through exciting and dangerous situations, so it is worth investing time in creating a character you will enjoy playing.\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s2\fi-576\li576\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0\fs26 2.1\tab What Makes a Protagonist\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\b0\f1\fs22 All Protagonists are composed of six elements:\par
\b STATISTICS (STATS):\b0  Core capabilities for every Protagonist.\par
\b DERIVED ATTRIBUTES:\b0  Ratings that indicate physical and mental resilience, derived from stats.\par
\b ARCHETYPE:\b0  The type of role your Protagonist performs, which informs how many skill points and Bonds he or she has.\par
\b SKILLS:\b0  What training and education your Protagonist has picked up from being taught, or from life in general.\par
\b RESOURCES:\b0  An abstract rating that reflects your Protagonist\rquote s access to useful equipment or items.\par
\b BONDS:\b0  The people and communities your Protagonist fights to protect.\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s2\fi-576\li576\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0\fs26 2.2\tab Protagonist Creation\par
\pard\cf0\b0\f1\fs22 Follow these steps to create a new Protagonist, or see \b HOW TO CREATE A PROTAGONIST\b0  on page \lang3081 7\lang1033  for a quick reference.\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s3\fi-720\li720\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0 2.2.1\tab STEP 0: Establish Harshness of Protagonist\rquote s Upbringing\par
\pard\cf0\b0\f1 Most Protagonist\rquote s upbringings will have been unremarkable \endash  but it\rquote s possible that yours grew up under especially challenging and punishing circumstances. For example, growing up amid a turbulent period of warfare or plague that killed most of those near-and-dear to the Protagonist. If you think that upbringing might have been harsh enough to scar your Protagonist, discuss it with your Game Moderator. Between you, decide whether the upbringing you envisage is best characterized by the descriptor \b Normal(-ish)\b0 , \b Harsh\b0 , or \b Very Harsh\b0 . See page \lang3081 9\lang1033  for a few examples of real-world disasters which could have brought tragedy to your Protagonist\rquote s childhood.\par
Usually, an upbringing warranting the descriptor \b Harsh\b0  will involve the Protagonist having spent at least 3-4 years of adolescence in a highly dangerous or adverse situation that only affected the specific region. This calamity is likely to have caused the untimely death of at least a couple of the character\rquote s immediate family.\par
For an upbringing to be considered \b Very Harsh\b0 , the whole of the Protagonists childhood and adolescence was likely marred by a dangerous, deadly, or otherwise toxic environment that was particular to their region. This terrible situation is likely to have resulted in the majority of the characters\rquote  family suffering greatly, with at least half having perished.\par
Any upbringing that isn\rquote t \b Harsh\b0  or \b Very Harsh\b0  is considered \b Normal(-ish).\b0\par
A harsher upbringing might make him or her a little stronger or hardier (since only the strong and hardy would have survived), but at the cost of mental scarring from the many horrific sights marring their childhood. \par
\pard\keep\keepn\s3\fi-720\li720\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0 2.2.2\tab STEP 1: Determine Statistics\par
\pard\cf0\b0\f1 Statistics are Strength (STR), Dexterity (DEX), Constitution (CON), Intelligence (INT), Power (POW), and Charisma (CHA). They range from 3 (the worst) to 18 (the best), with an average of 10 for an ordinary adult. Statistics represent core capabilities possessed by all Protagonists. All are important. (See \b DETAILED DESCRIPTION: STATISTICS\b0  on page \lang3081 8\lang1033 .)\par
\pard\sa120\sl276\slmult1 You can create stats in two ways: rolling them or assigning points. Pick a method.\par
\pard\fi-360\li720\sa200\sl276\slmult1\b 1.\tab ROLL STATS: \b0 For each stat roll 4D6, drop the lowest of the four dice, and add up the other three. Place the six rolls in whichever stats you like.\par
\pard\fi-360\li720\b 2.\tab ASSIGN STATS: \b0 Divide 72 points among the six stats however you like, or pick one of the sets from page \lang3081 9\lang1033  and assign each score to one statistic.\par
\pard\sa120\sl276\slmult1 After the basic values are assigned for each statistic, modify according to the Harshness Descriptor for the setting:\par
\pard\fi-360\li720\sa200\sl276\slmult1\f2\'b7\tab\f1 For Protagonists in \b Harsh\b0  settings: add 1 to \i either\i0  STR \i or\i0  CON (player\rquote s choice)\par
\f2\'b7\tab\f1 For Protagonists in \b Very Harsh\b0  settings: add 1 to \i both\i0  STR \i and\i0  CON\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s3\fi-720\li720\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0 2.2.3\tab STEP 2: Calculate Derived Attributes\par
\pard\cf0\b0\f1 Hit Points, Willpower Points, Sanity Points, and Breaking Point are derived from stats. They represent physical and mental resilience. When your Protagonist is hurt, exercises mental fortitude, or is traumatized, those scores can drop. If your Protagonist has a STR score that is outside the average range (9\emdash 12) he or she also has a modifier to the damage inflicted from hand-to-hand combat. (See \b DETAILED DESCRIPTION: DERIVED ATTRIBUTES & DAMAGE BONUS\b0  on page \lang3081 10\lang1033 .)\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s3\fi-720\li720\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0 2.2.4\tab STEP 3: Select Archetype\par
\pard\cf0\b0\f1 What does your Protagonist do for a living (or just to stay alive)? Archetype dictates what skills your Protagonist has, his or her basic resource level, and the number of Bonds he or she possesses. (See \b DETAILED DESCRIPTION: ARCHETYPES\b0  on page \lang3081 11\lang1033 .) \par
\pard\keep\keepn\s3\fi-720\li720\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0 2.2.5\tab STEP 4: Calculate Resources Rating\par
\pard\cf0\b0\f1 The Resources rating is a number between 0 and 20 that reflects the Protagonist\rquote s access to valuable or useful equipment. A Protagonist\rquote s base Resources rating is dictated by his or her Archetype, however during later steps, you can sacrifice other potential bonus skills in favor of a higher resources score; conversely, you can agree to drop Resources rating of 0 (entirely without access to resources) and receive additional skills. (See \b DETAILED DESCRIPTION: RESOURCES\b0  on page \lang3081 18\lang1033 .)\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s3\fi-720\li720\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0 2.2.6\tab STEP 5: Define Bonds\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\b0\f1 Bonds indicate the strength of relationships with the most important people and communities in your Protagonist\rquote s life \emdash  like a spouse, child, a long-time travelling companion, or a local community of people. Bonds help Protagonists resist mental trauma\emdash but as your Protagonist\rquote s life falls apart under the stress of the Mythos-haunted world, Bonds deteriorate. \par
There are \b two types of Bonds\b0  \endash  bonds with individuals and bonds with an entire community. The latter reflect the Protagonist\rquote s standing as part of the community and his or her ability to influence the group. \par
Each Individual Bond has a value that starts equal to your Protagonist\rquote s Charisma (CHA). \par
\pard Each Community Bond has a default value equal to half the Protagonist\rquote s Resources rating, however during creation of the Protagonist the player may elect to sacrifice potential skills in favor of a higher value. Conversely, the player may elect to take a Community Bond with a value of 1 (lowest possible social standing) and receive additional skills. (See \b DETAILED DESCRIPTION: BONDS\b0  on page \lang3081 23\lang1033 .)\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s3\fi-720\li720\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0 2.2.7\tab STEP 6: Select Bonus & Adversity Skills\par
\pard\cf0\b0\f1 Skills require special training, and come from schooling, experience, or personal interest. Skills are measured from 0% (no training) to 99% (foremost expert in the world). (See \b DETAILED DESCRIPTION: SKILLS\b0  on page \lang3081 27\lang1033 .)\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s3\fi-720\li720\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0 2.2.8\tab STEP 7: Determine Mental Damage from Harsh Environments\par
\pard\cf0\b0\f1 Protagonists that have grown up in difficult and brutal conditions are likely to have picked up some mental scarring along the way. This can leave them hardened to certain types of traumatic stimuli, distant from those around them, or afflicted with mental disorders. (see \b DETAILED DESCRIPTION: MENTAL DAMAGE FROM HARSH UPBRINGING\b0 , page \lang3081 36\lang1033 .)\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s3\fi-720\li720\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0 2.2.9\tab STEP 8: Add the Final Details\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\b0\f1 Start filling in the details that make your Protagonist interesting.\par
How old is your Protagonist? What does he or she look like? Where did he or she grow up?\par
What\rquote s your Protagonist\rquote s name? What is your Protagonist\rquote s role in the community and what\rquote s your personal life like?\par
And why, despite all the terrifying dangers, does your Protagonist venture out to pursue adventure or investigate weirdness?\par
