\pard\sa120\sl276\slmult1\cf0\b0\f1\fs22 The derived attributes \emdash  Hit Points, Willpower Points, Sanity Points, and Breaking Point \emdash  represent your Protagonist\rquote s physical and mental toughness. \par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1 Damage Bonus reflects whether his or her brawn (or lack thereof) will affect damage inflicted through brawling and hand-to-hand weapons.\par
\b HIT POINTS (HP):\b0  Hit Points represent how much damage your Protagonist can sustain. When the Protagonist is injured, subtract the damage from HP. At 2 HP, your Protagonist falls unconscious. At 0 HP, your Protagonist dies. Hit Points are regained through rest and medical attention.\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\qc\b\i Hit Points equal CON plus STR, divided by two and rounded up.\par
\pard\i0 WILLPOWER POINTS (WP):\b0  Willpower Points represent mental fortitude. They fall when your Protagonist attempts to suppress the symptoms of mental illness (see \b RESISTING INSANITY\b0  on page \lang3081 74\lang1033 ), becomes exhausted (see \b EXHAUSTION\b0  on page \lang3081 43\lang1033 ), attempts to resist persuasion, suffers emotional burnout (see \b FUMBLE\b0  on page \lang3081 40\lang1033 ), or tries to fuel unnatural phenomena. At 2 WP, your Protagonist has a temporary emotional collapse. At 0 WP, your Protagonist falls unconscious. Willpower Points are regained with rest. (See \b WILLPOWER POINTS\b0  on page \lang3081 42\lang1033 .)\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\qc\b\i Willpower Points equal POW.\par
\pard\i0 SANITY POINTS (SAN):\b0  Sanity Points represent mental health: how much mental trauma, or exposure to the unnatural your Protagonist can endure before going insane. In moments of mental trauma your Protagonist must make a \b Sanity test\b0  by rolling SAN or lower on 1D100. If that fails, your Protagonist loses SAN. (See \b SANITY\b0  on page \lang3081 65\lang1033 .) Sanity Points are regained through remedial care or by overcoming unnatural threats. At 0 Sanity Points, your Protagonist goes irretrievably insane and becomes an NPC permanently under the control of the Game Moderator.\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1 A Protagonist\rquote s starting Sanity Points depends on the Harshness of his or her upbringing \endash  the harsher the situation, the more brutality and horror the Protagonist has been scarred by.   \par
\pard\sl276\slmult1\qc\b\i Normal(ish) Setting: Sanity Points begin equal to POW\'d75.\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\qc Harsh or Very Harsh Setting: Sanity Points begin equal to POW\'d74.\par
\pard\i0 BREAKING POINT:\b0  The Breaking Point is the point at which loss of SAN triggers a long-term mental disorder. (See \b INSANITY AND DISORDERS\b0  on page \lang3081 68\lang1033 .)\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\qc\b\i A Protagonist\rquote s Breaking Point equals SAN minus POW.\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\b0\i0 The instant the Protagonist\rquote s SAN reaches the Breaking Point, he or she gains a disorder. Reset the Breaking Point to equal the new SAN score minus POW.\par
\pard\sl276\slmult1\b MAXIMUM SAN: \b0 The is the absolute maximum number of Sanity Points your Protagonist can EVER reach, by any means. Learning more about the true nature of the Cthulhu Mythos (represented by the Unnatural skill) reduces this number.\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\qc\b\i A Protagonist\rquote s Maximum SAN always equals 99 minus skill rating in the Unnatural Skill.\par
\pard\i0 RECOVERY SAN:\b0  This is the highest Sanity Point total that your Protagonist can possibly achieve through mundane methods \endash  relaxation, personal pursuits, caring for loved ones, and seeking help for mental illness. See \b RECOVERING SANITY\b0  on page \lang3081 75\lang1033 .\par
\pard\qc\b A Protagonist\rquote s Recovery SAN equals POW\'d75, regardless of the harshness of the setting.\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\qc\i If this number would be higher than Max SAN, Recovery SAN equals Max SAN.\par
\pard\i0 DAMAGE BONUS:\b0  High or low Strength modifies the \b DAMAGE\b0  the Protagonist inflicts through successful unarmed and hand-to-hand weapon attacks (see page \lang3081 48\lang1033 ). This modifier to damage should be recorded on the Protagonist sheet for later reference.\par
