\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\b0\f1\fs22 Each Protagonist is a representative of a broad category of character types, usually related to the job he or she performs in the game world. Each such category is called an \b Archetype\b0 . \par
An Archetype says a lot about a Protagonist. It grants a \ldblquote kit\rdblquote  of appropriate skills. It also determines the number of Bonds your Protagonist has when the game begins, and his or her starting Resource level.\par
\b RECOMMENDED STATS:\b0  Some Archetypes require people who are particularly fit, stable, or smart. This means the recommended stats should be 10 or higher \emdash  or at least they were when your Protagonist first started out being the Archetype. \par
\pard\b ARCHETYPAL SKILLS:\b0  Each Archetype has a predefined kit of skills with scores that replace the default skill ratings. This represents the baseline training, experience, and education for that Archetype. See \b DETAILED DESCRIPTION: SKILLS\b0  on page \lang3081 27\lang1033  for their uses.\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\b RESOURCES:\b0  Each Archetype dictates a base value for the Resources rating. \par
\b BONDS\b0 : Each Archetype dictates the number of Bonds your Protagonist begins with. Difficult and trying Archetypes mean fewer Bonds but more skills. The player can decide whether each of these Bonds refers to:\par
\pard\fi-360\li765\sa200\sl276\slmult1\f2\'b7\tab\f1 a relationship to an individual (Individual Bonds) or \par
\f2\'b7\tab\f1 standing within a community (Community Bonds).\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s3\fi-720\li720\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0 2.5.1\tab Customizing Your Protagonist With Other Skills\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\b0\f1 Don\rquote t worry if your Protagonist at this point looks like a generic representative of his or her chosen Archetype. While the Archetype defines a core set of abilities, those skills and ratings don\rquote t represent the full range of everything your Protagonist can do. \par
Later in the character generation process you will have opportunities to pick other skills they are also good at. There are two different types of skill picks:\par
\pard\fi-360\li720\caps\f2\'b7\tab\b\f1 Adversity Skill Point Picks\b0\caps0  (see page \lang3081 18\lang1033 ) represent abilities your Protagonist has because of the harsh environment that he or she grew up in. These picks can only be used to enhance a few specific skills, and cannot be traded in for other benefits.\par
\caps\f2\'b7\tab\b\f1 Bonus Skill Point Picks\b0\caps0  (see page \lang3081 26\lang1033 ) represent hobbies and general experience he or she learned above and beyond the basics associated with the Archetype. You start with \ul ten\ulnone  such bonus picks to use later in the Protagonist generation process. These picks \i can\i0  be traded in for other advantages like increased availability of resources-at-hand or standing in a community.\par
