\pard\keep\keepn\s4\sb40\sl276\slmult1\cf1\i\f0 Pushing the Limits\par
\pard\sa120\sl276\slmult1\cf0\i0\f1 As indicated in the table, it is typically only possible for your Protagonist to keep 6 points of Resources on their person (\lquote at-hand\rquote ) and another 6 points \lquote stowed\rquote  in a handy vehicle or on a handy animal. These aren\rquote t hard and fast limits, but represent what can comfortably be carried/transported without impacting travel speed and convenience. If situations arise where the Protagonist really needs to carry more (e.g., carry the entire 10 points of Permanent Resources by hand while fleeing a burning building), it is up to the Game Moderator to decide what is possible and what impacts might arise from your Protagonist or vehicle being \lquote overloaded\rquote . The Game Moderator might rule this has an impact on the rate of travel, or require some kind of skill test to keep moving forward under excess load. \par
Generally, stretching the limits beyond 12 points carried \lquote at hand\rquote  or 12 points \lquote stowed\rquote  is impossible.\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1 There is no limit to the amount of Resources rating points that can be \lquote in storage\rquote  at a fixed location (e.g., a home base or workshop).\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s4\sb40\sl276\slmult1\cf1\i\f0 Which Rating for a Test?\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\i0\f1 Any time your Protagonist\rquote s Resources rating is the subject of a test, the effective rating number that is used should reflect the situation. It should be determined by the amount of Resources available to your Protagonist at that moment. If he or she is at home base, that will probably be the full Permanent Resources amount; if your Protagonist is close to his or her vehicle (or pack animal) that might be the \lquote at-hand\rquote  value PLUS the stowed value. If your Protagonist is far away from both home base and vehicle/animal, the number is likely to be just the \lquote at-hand\rquote  number.\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s4\sb40\sl276\slmult1\cf1\i\f0 Which Rating for NPC Reactions?\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\i0\f1 When using Resources as a means of determining Non-Player Character reactions, the rating that is used also depends on the situation. Does the NPC in question know all about your Protagonist\rquote s reputation as a \lquote wealthy\rquote  sort? If so, maybe the full Permanent Resources score can be used even if only some of that wealth is currently on display. Alternatively, if the NPC is suspicious of your Protagonist, it might be hard to get him or her to believe in the existence of any resources beyond what they can see for themselves.\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s3\fi-720\li720\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0 2.7.3\tab The Bag of Tricks\par
\pard\sa120\sl276\slmult1\cf0\b0\f1 The higher your Protagonist\rquote s effective Resources rating, the higher the likelihood that his or her accessible personal cache of items may contain something helpful to a situation or problem.\par
\pard\fi-360\li720\sa200\sl276\slmult1\f2\'b7\tab\f1 In situations where \b non-specialist resources or items\b0  are needed, simply make a test of your Protagonist\rquote s Resources \'d7 5. Success means that something helpful was found. \par
\f2\'b7\tab\f1 In cases where a situation requires a \b very specialized\b0  resource or item, the Game Moderator might rule it is too rare to find in your Protagonist\rquote s pool of gear. Alternatively, the GM \i may\i0  still permit a test of Resources \'d7 5 roll to locate the rare equipment \endash  \ul\i but\ulnone\i0  rule that success will \b permanently reduce\b0  your Protagonist\rquote s Resources rating by a few points (the number being at the Game Moderator\rquote s discretion).\par
\pard Depending on the specific game setting, the difficulty of Resources tests and the quality of the items unearthed through successful rolls may vary. See \b SCROUNGING EQUIPMENT\b0  starting page \lang3081 60\lang1033 .\par
\pard\sl276\slmult1 Rules of Thumb:\par
\pard\fi-360\li720\sa200\sl276\slmult1\f2\'b7\tab\f1 Tests to find items or resource types that are considered \i Hard to Get\i0  in the setting are made at HALF the Protagonist\rquote s effective Resources rating\par
\f2\'b7\tab\f1 Tests to find items or resource types that are considered \i Very Hard to Get\i0  or \i Impossible to Get\i0  in the setting are made at QUARTER the Protagonist\rquote s effective Resources rating\par
\f2\'b7\tab\f1 A test that is a standard success, but which is only just under the target number might yield a sub-standard version of the item or resource. A critical success will always yield the best possible quality available.\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s3\fi-720\li720\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0 2.7.4\tab Checkboxes and Per-Adventure Limits\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\b0\f1 While your Protagonist\rquote s personal Resources can prove helpful during an adventure, there are practical limits to the number of times that items can be pulled from it during a single adventure. \par
\pard After each Resources test resulting in success, place a check mark in one of the Resource Check boxes on the Protagonist\rquote s character sheet. When all the boxes are full, the Protagonist\rquote s resources pool is temporarily exhausted and can\rquote t contribute anything more until he or she has some downtime to replenish or reorganize it (see\lang3081  \lang1033\b\caps Replenishing Resources, Removing Checkmarks\b0\caps0 , page \lang3081 23\lang1033 ).\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s3\fi-720\li720\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0 2.7.5\tab Pooling Resources\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\b0\f1 Sometimes, it may be appropriate for two or more Protagonists to pool their personal caches of items to improve the likelihood of finding a rare but crucial component. Any Protagonist can contribute items to the pool, as long as he or she hasn\rquote t temporarily exhausted their resource pool (by filling all check boxes).\par
When making a roll to search such a \b combined\b0  resource pool, the effective Resources rating of the collection is equal to the \b highest\b0  individual Resources rating included in the collection \b plus ONE FIFTH\b0  of the Resources rating of every additional individual stockpile added to the heap (round fractions up). This reflects duplication of items or functions.\par
Success on a combined test causes a check mark to be placed on the sheet of the Protagonist whose FULL Resources rating was used. Others who contributed a smaller amount to the total do not receive a check mark.\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s3\fi-720\li720\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0 2.7.6\tab Losing Resources\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\b0\f1 A Protagonist\rquote s Resources rating may decrease due to events that occur during play:\par
\pard\fi-360\li720\sa200\sl276\slmult1\f2\'b7\tab\f1 As described above, producing a highly specialized item as the result of a Resources test may cause the Permanent Resources rating to be reduced by one or more.\par
\f2\'b7\tab\f1 If the Protagonist is robbed or otherwise loses control of a significant amount of his or her personal equipment, the Game Moderator may decide this warrants a loss of a proportional amount of Resources rating.\par
\f2\'b7\tab\f1 If a proportion of the Protagonist\rquote s resources are stowed in a vehicle or on a pack animal, the theft or destruction of the conveyance is likely to cause some or all to be lost, the exact proportion decided by the Game Moderator.\par
\f2\'b7\tab\f1 If a proportion of the Protagonist\rquote s resources are stored in a fixed location, a disaster that outright destroys or significantly damages the location will likewise cause a reduction to permanent Resources. The points lost are based on the number of \lquote in storage\rquote  rating points stored at the location (i.e., not carried or stowed). The same loss may occur if the permanent location becomes invaded or overtaken by a hostile party \endash  although in that situation the loss might be temporary, assuming the Protagonists can win back their former stronghold at some future date.\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1 Whenever Resource rating decreases, the player should recalculate the \ldblquote at-hand\rdblquote /stowed/stored breakdown of points as well as the number of check boxes available to the Protagonist. \par
\pard\keep\keepn\s3\fi-720\li720\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0 2.7.7\tab Increasing the Resources Rating During Play\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\b0\f1 During a \i Cthulhu Eternal\i0  adventure your Protagonist may gain access to a cache of items ripe for the taking. When this occurs, the Game Moderator will decide the number of Resources rating points each Protagonist might potentially plunder. For a small find this might be modest (1 point or 1D2 points), but for a massive discovery it could be a healthy improvement (1D6 or higher).\par
Increasing your Protagonist\rquote s Permanent Resources rating requires a die roll. With percentile dice, attempt to roll above \b Permanent Resources rating \'d7 5.\b0  This reflects the fact that the more your Protagonist already owns, the harder it is to acquire additional new items he or she does not already have. If the test is successful, increase the Resources rating by the amount or die roll indicated by the GM.\par
Whenever Resource rating increases, the player should recalculate the \ldblquote at-hand\rdblquote /stowed/stored breakdown of points as well as the number of check boxes available to the Protagonist.\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s3\fi-720\li720\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0 2.7.8\tab Replenishing Resources, Removing Checkmarks\par
\pard\cf0\b0\f1 The Game Moderator will determine when your Protagonist group can take the time to replenish or reorganize their Resources pools. Usually this happens between missions, expeditions, or adventures (see \b DOWNTIME\b0 , page \lang3081 76\lang1033 ). Once the Protagonists have invested an appropriate period of downtime all check marks can be erased from the character sheet.\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s2\fi-576\li576\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0\fs26 2.8\tab Detailed Description: Bonds\par
\pard\cf0\b0\f1\fs22 Bonds measure your Protagonist\rquote s relationships with the vital people and societies in his or her life: loved ones, family members, and wider communities. A Bond can protect your Protagonist from SAN loss (see \b PROJECTING ONTO A BOND\b0  on page \lang3081 75\lang1033 ) or offer a chance to repress the effects of a disorder or temporary insanity (see \b REPRESSING INSANITY\b0  on page \lang3081 75\lang1033 ).\par
Bonds are not merely motivations or things your Protagonist likes. They are your Protagonist\rquote s connection to humanity and its social structures. A Protagonist with no Bonds is more susceptible to psychological trauma than one who has people waiting back home.\par
Your Protagonist\rquote s Archetype determines how many Bonds your Protagonist begins with. The more trying and time-consuming the Archetype, the fewer Bonds your Protagonist is able to maintain.\par
There are two distinct types of Bonds, each handled slightly differently \endash  they are \b Individual Bonds\b0  and \b Community Bonds. \b0 When creating a Protagonist, you are free to choose which of his or her starting bonds is of each type.\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s3\fi-720\li720\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0 2.8.1\tab Individual Bonds\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\b0\f1 An Individual Bond is an emotional connection to a single person. It could be familial or marital, or it could just be a close friendship or association. To qualify as an Individual Bond the person must be someone the Protagonist believes (hopes?) to be still alive. \par
Each Individual Bond begins with a score equal to your Protagonist\rquote s CHA. It cannot typically go above this value.\par
\pard\b Sample Individual Bonds\par
\pard\fi-360\li720\sa200\b0\f2\'b7\tab\f1 Spouse or ex-spouse\i\par
\i0\f2\'b7\tab\f1 Son or daughter\i\par
\i0\f2\'b7\tab\f1 Parent or grandparent\i\par
\i0\f2\'b7\tab\f1 Best friend\i\par
\i0\f2\'b7\tab\f1 Members of the same gang or band (see \b BONDS FORMED THROUGH SHARED ADVERSITY\b0 , below)\i\par
\i0\f2\'b7\tab\f1 Spiritual counsellor\i\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s4\sb40\sl276\slmult1\cf1\f0 Changes to Individual Bonds During Play\par
\pard\cf0\i0\f1 Bonds\rquote  scores often deteriorate because of your Protagonist\rquote s experiences of the horrors of the Mythos-haunted world. A Bond increases if it is cultivated between adventures (see \b DOWNTIME\b0  on page \lang3081 76\lang1033 ). An Individual Bond can never have a score higher than your Protagonist\rquote s CHA. Any time CHA drops, each Individual Bond drops by the same amount.\par
Individual Bonds are vulnerable. If the Protagonist learns that the individual has died or gone permanently insane, the Bond is destroyed. The Bond is also permanently broken when its score drops to 0 (see \b BROKEN BONDS\b0 , nearby).\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s3\fi-720\li720\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0 2.8.2\tab Community Bonds\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\b0\f1 A Community Bond is a relationship between the Protagonist and a broader community of individuals; it reflects the Protagonist\rquote s status within that community, and the likelihood of other people following his or her instructions or desires. \par
A community may be a geographical association of people or it may be a society of like-minded individuals (e.g., a club, congregation, or association). A Protagonist can have more than one Community Bond, each describing his or her status within the hierarchy of a different societal structure.\par
Community Bonds are measured on a scale of 1 to 20, with an indicative meaning shown below:\par
\pard\sl276\slmult1\b Rating\tab\tab What the Rating Represents\par
\pard\b0 1\tab\tab Disgraced member; on the verge of being banished from the society.\par
2-4\tab\tab Shunned member of the community; someone who is actively looked down on by most\par
5-8\tab\tab Standard member of the community; one of the pack, whose opinion is unlikely to matter\par
9-12\tab\tab Well-regarded member of the community; favorably viewed by many other members\par
\pard\fi-1440\li1440 13-16\tab Important member of the community; respected by most other members\par
17-18\tab Influential member of community, involved in most decision-making; liked by most\par
19\tab An extremely influential member of the community, looked up to by virtually everyone\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1 20\tab\tab Top-tier of leadership in the community; the head honcho.\par
\pard If a Community Bond is chosen during the creation of your Protagonist, it typically begins with a default rating of \ul half\ulnone  the Protagonist\rquote s Permanent Resources rating, rounded up (see \b RESOURCES\b0  on page \lang3081 18\lang1033 ). In a few cases, a Protagonist\rquote s Archetype indicates that he or she has a Community Bond with a certain fixed rating \endash  the final rating should be either that value or half the Permanent Resources rating, whichever is higher. \par
This value can be optionally increased during the creation of your Protagonist by sacrificing one or more \b BONUS SKILL POINT\b0  picks (see page \lang3081 26\lang1033 ); the first skill pick sacrificed in this manner gives a bonus of +5 to the Community Bond\rquote s rating; each subsequent sacrifice adds +2 (to a maximum of 20). \par
It is also possible to elect for your Protagonist to take a Community Bond with a rating of 1 (and suffer the social effects of being a pariah to fellow members) and receive one extra Bonus Skill Point Pick to use on purchasing skills later in the process.\par
\b Sample Community Bonds\par
\pard\fi-360\li720\sa200\b0\f2\'b7\tab\f1 Group which shelters in the same place\i\par
\i0\f2\'b7\tab\f1 Church or support group\i\par
\i0\f2\'b7\tab\f1 Craft or trade guild\i\par
\i0\f2\'b7\tab\f1 Secret society\i\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s4\sb40\sl276\slmult1\cf1\f0 Changes to Community Bonds During Play\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\i0\f1 The rating for a Community Bond applies individually to every member of that community, and to the community as a whole. If a Community Bond decreases in value, the relationship with each member of the community deteriorates. A Community Bond is permanently broken when its score drops to 0 (and the Protagonist is likely cast out of the nominated community). \par
If the community itself is entirely destroyed (e.g., every member killed or sent insane), or if the Protagonist permanently leaves it (e.g., by relocating to live in a new region) the bond is destroyed.\par
If a Community Bond is broken by either means, the Protagonist will likely suffer negative impacts (see \b BROKEN BONDS\b0 , nearby).\par
During play, events may arise where the reactions of NPCs from the Protagonist\rquote s bonded community (or the community as a whole) have an impact. In some cases, the Protagonist may instigate such situations (e.g., by requesting aid from the community or trying to convince them of impending danger). In such situations the Game Moderator may ask for a test against \b Community Bond Rating \'d7 5.\b0  Success means that the NPC or the community reacts favorably.\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s3\fi-720\li720\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0 2.8.3\tab Describing Bonds\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\b0\f1 Identify each Individual and Community Bond: \ldblquote My Wife.\rdblquote  \ldblquote My Husband and Kids.\rdblquote  \ldblquote My church congregation.\rdblquote  \ldblquote The Society of Amateur Sleuths.\rdblquote  \par
An Individual Bond must be a real person or group of people who the Protagonist believes to be alive, and with which there is some (potential) opportunity to interact. \par
A Community Bond must be a real group who recognizes the Protagonist as a member.\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s3\fi-720\li720\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0 2.8.4\tab Broken Bonds\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\b0\f1 When a Bond deteriorates, that relationship becomes strained. Exactly what shape that takes in play is up to you and the Game Moderator (playing the NPCs). \par
Bonds often fall apart because of events beyond your Protagonist\rquote s control. An example for Individual Bonds: your Protagonist\rquote s husband might leave for another woman. An example for Community Bonds: a new leader might ascend to power who is actively antagonistic towards your Protagonist.\par
If such a disaster harms the subject of a Bond, that reduces the Bond\rquote s value by 1D4. If that disaster permanently removes the subject of the Bond, that Bond is gone. Cross it off the sheet.\par
\pard When damage to a Bond reduces it to 0, the relationship is damaged beyond repair. Cross it off the sheet. The only way to regain a Bond with that character or community is to build it from scratch as if it had never existed (see \b DOWNTIME\b0  on page \lang3081 76\lang1033  for details on creating new Bonds).\par
The breaking of any Bond is almost certainly traumatic and is likely to trigger a Sanity test due to Helplessness (see page \lang3081 67\lang1033 ).\par
When you cross a Bond off your Protagonist\rquote s character sheet, don\rquote t erase it. After all, there\rquote s no forgetting a vital relationship that went bad. \par
\pard\keep\keepn\s3\fi-720\li720\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0 2.8.5\tab Bonds Forged Through Shared Adversity\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\b0\f1 Protagonists often band together into small tight-knit groups, to enhance their chances. This is true when the group is alone in the wasteland; it\rquote s often also true even when they are outsiders in a larger settlement. If those tight-knit groups go through terrifying ordeals together, there is a strong chance that they will become psychologically bound together through that shared experience. \par
In game terms, groups of Protagonists tend to form individual bonds to one another when they spend most of their time fighting the forces of the Mythos. Whenever your Protagonist is part of a team that completes a harrowing adventure, there\rquote s a chance of such trauma-generated bonds forming or deepening. This is the case if the scenario played out in a way where:\par
\pard\fi-360\li720\sa200\sl276\slmult1\f2\'b7\tab\f1 One or more members of the team suffered temporary insanity, or\par
\f2\'b7\tab\f1 One or more members of the team gained a new psychological disorder, or\par
\f2\'b7\tab\f1 One or more members of the team died or was incapacitated by physical injuries, or\par
\f2\'b7\tab\f1 Any other event occurred that the Game Moderator thinks was shocking enough to constitute severe trauma.\par
\pard In the downtime after the adventure (see \b DOWNTIME\b0  on page \lang3081 76\lang1033 ), all Protagonists that made it back must make a SAN test. If the roll succeeds, nothing changes. If your Protagonist fails the SAN roll, he or she gains or strengthens an individual bond with EACH fellow Protagonist who also made it through the same trauma (up to a maximum of five fellow Protagonists). \par
For each such fellow trauma-sufferer,\par
\pard\fi-360\li825\sa200\sl276\slmult1\f2\'b7\tab\f1 If your Protagonist has \b no previous bond\b0  with that person, he or she gains a brand-new individual Bond to that person at a rating equal to half your Protagonist\rquote s CHA. Add the new Bond to your Protagonist\rquote s character sheet. This focusing of attention comes at a detrimental cost to other pre-existing Bonds \endash  you must lose 1D4 points from one other bond of your choice (either an Individual or Community Bond).\par
\f2\'b7\tab\f1 If your Protagonist \b already has an Individual Bond\b0  with that person, the bond is increased by 1D4 points (up to a maximum value equal to CHA); at the same time 1 point must be subtracted from another bond of the player\rquote s choice (either an Individual or Community Bond). Note that even if all your Protagonist\rquote s existing bonds are already at the maximum score (and hence can\rquote t increase), you still need to pick a bond to weaken by 1.\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1 Remember that if a Bond is ever reduced to 0 or less it is broken, as per the previous section. \par
When choosing a Bond to weaken during this process you CANNOT pick a bond to an individual who was with your Protagonist on the recently completed adventure. You MAY, however, pick an Individual Bond gained from an earlier shared traumatic encounter.\par
Rather than treating this as a mechanical process, you and your Game Moderator are encouraged to work together to describe the changed dynamic between your Protagonist and those around them. If points have been gained with fellow adventurers, does that mean they are beginning to feel comfort that their colleagues will always have their back? Or has the shared experience kindled a romance of sorts? Conversely, if a bond has been weakened, does that mean the Protagonist has been neglecting a member of their circle of friends and both are now feeling their friendship is slipping away? \par
If a community bond has weakened does it mean that the excessive time spent socializing with the tight-knit group has alienated others in the community to the point that they have lost confidence in the Protagonist? Or has he or she just missed so many gatherings that their standing as a high-status member of society has eroded?\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s2\fi-576\li576\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0\fs26 2.9\tab Detailed Description: Bonus Skill Points\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\b0\f1\fs22 The skill package associated with your Protagonist\rquote s Archetype coupled with the Adversity skills from the harshness of his or her upbringing, represent his or her core proficiencies. But they certainly aren\rquote t the full story about everything the Protagonist is good at. \par
Each Protagonist \b begins with ten Bonus Skill Point Picks\b0 . Each pick provides a boost of 20 points to whichever skill it is applied. Alternatively, some of these skill picks can be \b traded-in\b0  for non-skill benefits instead (see box nearby). \par
When applying a skill pick to a skill which has NOT been set by the Protagonist\rquote s Archetype or increased through Adversity Skill Picks, then add the 20 to its \b base rating\b0 . Otherwise, add 20 to its \b current score\b0 . This allows your Protagonist to specialize in certain Archetypal skills or to learn a little about skills not included in his or her Archetype. You can even boost a single skill more than once, adding +20 each time. \par
Unless the Game Moderator says otherwise, you can\rquote t raise a skill higher than 80% during Protagonist creation. You must assign (or trade-in) all bonus points to skills before play begins.\par
