\pard\keep\keepn\s3\fi-720\li720\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0 4.3.1\tab Dodging and Fighting Back\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\b0\f1 Your Protagonist can Dodge or fight back against an incoming attack even before your Protagonist\rquote s DEX order in a turn. If you do this, it becomes your Protagonist\rquote s single action for that turn. A Protagonist who has already taken another action that turn can\rquote t Dodge or fight back until the next turn.\par
A roll to Dodge opposes \i all \i0 hand-to-hand attacks that turn. It lets your Protagonist duck behind cover to evade all ranged attacks that turn if cover is near. Dodging never inflicts damage.\par
Fighting back blocks \i all \i0 hand-to-hand attacks that turn. If you win the contest, you take no damage. It does not protect you against ranged attacks unless you\rquote re close enough to push the ranged weapon away. As part of your fighting back roll, choose one offensive action \endash  \b\caps attack, called shot, disarm,\b0\caps0  or \b\caps pin \b0\endash  \caps0 against a single attacker. If your roll beats that attacker\rquote s roll, your Protagonist takes no damage and your Protagonist\rquote s action affects the attacker.\par
In order to Dodge or fight back, your Protagonist must know an attack is coming and be physically able to block or evade it. If your Protagonist is pinned, if the attack occurs before he or she realizes it, or if your Protagonist can\rquote t see or hear the attacker, your Protagonist can\rquote t Dodge or fight back.\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s3\fi-720\li720\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0 4.3.2\tab Dodging Ranged Attacks\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\b0\f1 An ordinary Dodge roll can avoid a slow-moving ranged attack, such as an arrow or a thrown weapon. \par
\lang3081 Nobody can react as fast as bullets and shrapnel, but your Protagonist can use Dodge to scramble for cover. If your Protagonist is near enough to move to cover and knows gunfire or an explosion is imminent, make a Dodge roll for the Protagonist to get behind the cover. If there\rquote s no cover, Dodging does no good. This is why people get nervous when guns come out.\lang1033\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s3\fi-720\li720\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0 4.3.3\tab Defending After Attacking\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\b0\f1 When your turn comes up, declare your Protagonist\rquote s action \caps\emdash\b  attack, called shot, disarm, or pin\b0\caps0  \emdash  and make the roll. Your Protagonist can harm, disarm or pin only one target per turn (the attack might hurt others, but all attacks have a single target).\par
A roll to attack, disarm, pin, or make a called shot also opposes each \b Unarmed Combat\b0  and \b Melee Weapons\b0  attack against your Protagonist until your Protagonist\rquote s next action. If an attack fails to overcome your roll, it does no harm.\par
To oppose an attack, your Protagonist must know the attack is coming. That requires seeing or hearing the attacker. The Protagonist must \i also \i0 be physically able to block the attack, if it is melee. A pinned Protagonist can\rquote t defend, nor can a Protagonist who has already successfully pinned a target.\par
An attack roll with a ranged weapon does not oppose attack rolls against your Protagonist.\par
