\clbrdrl\brdrw10\brdrs\clbrdrt\brdrw10\brdrs\clbrdrr\brdrw10\brdrs\clbrdrb\brdrw10\brdrs \cellx10461\pard\intbl\sl276\slmult1 The Lethality rating replaces the need to roll lots of separate attacks and lots of dice for damage. Without it, a massively damaging attack might require several separate attacks and damage rolls to afflict many different targets. In the middle of combat, rolling that much breaks the tension. \par
If you\rquote d rather roll damage the old way, it\rquote s 1D6 damage for every 3% of Lethality. So a weapon with 35% would do 12D6 HP damage.\cell\row\pard\sb120\sa200\sl276\slmult1 With explosive weapons, Kill Radius attacks don\rquote t need to be as precise as ordinary attacks; hitting a zone within the Kill Radius of a target is enough. That adds +20% to the chance to hit.\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1 A failed attack roll means the Kill Radius lands harmlessly outside the intended area. The attack does no harm\emdash but may still suppress targets (see \b SUPPRESSION\b0 , below). Whether a failed Kill Radius attack does unwanted collateral damage is up to the Game Moderator.\par
\b MANY TARGETS:\b0  A single attack with a Kill Radius usually affects everyone in the Kill Radius. If that doesn\rquote t make sense for the situation, the Game Moderator can decide who gets hit.\par
The Game Moderator is welcome to let players roll the Lethality results for NPCs to speed things up. But really, you need to roll Lethality only for characters who are important enough to track in detail. Since even a failed Lethality roll inflicts between 2 and 20 damage, it\rquote s safe to just assume that most humans caught in a Kill Radius are either dead or incapacitated.\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s3\fi-720\li720\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0 4.6.2\tab Selective Fire\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\b0\f1 Some small arms, like submachine guns and assault rifles, have selective fire. The shooter chooses how it\rquote s used; each pull of the trigger can fire a single shot, a short burst, a long burst, a short spray, or a long spray. A weapon set for single shots attacks normally. A burst or a spray has a Lethality rating.\par
A short burst fires three bullets in one trigger pull. It affects a single target. A long burst fires five shots with a Kill Radius of 1 yard. Short and long sprays empty the magazine faster, but cover a larger Kill Radius. Some firearms allow only single shots or short bursts (\ldblquote three-round bursts\rdblquote ). \par
\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s2\fi-576\li576\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0\fs26 4.7\tab Explosions\par
\pard\cf0\b0\f1\fs22 If your Protagonist wants to disable or destroy a structure or vehicle, an explosive or other form of Lethal attack might be their best bet. Such large objects have their own Hit Points (see \b VEHICLES,\b0  page \lang3081 64\lang1033 ), and they are considered huge targets (see \b HUGE\b0 , page \lang3081 54\lang1033 ).\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1 For example, if your Protagonist wanted to gain entry into a bank vault, he or she might try lobbing a hand grenade at its door. The GM might rule that the safe has 20HP and an Armor rating of 10. Assuming the grenade lands such that the safe is within its kill radius (10 yards from where it lands), the safe will take damage. Because the object is treated like a HUGE target, the normal Lethality 15% damage is translated into an automatic 15 HP damage reduced by Armor down to 5 HP. So, while the explosion makes a lot of noise, the safe is only a quarter broken into. Time to get some more grenades.\par
\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s2\fi-576\li576\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0\fs26 4.8\tab Fear in Combat\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\b0\f1\fs22 Being involved in combat is inherently frightening for most people. However, certain types of attacks which devastate an entire area are especially terror-inducing. When faced with such destruction \endash  whether from a mundane weapon (e.g., \lang3081 a burst from a Tommy gun\lang1033 ) or something supernatural \endash  primal instinct kicks in to prevent a person from placing themselves in mortal peril.\par
The GM can nominate that any massively damaging attack is \b Terror-Inducing.\b0  Any character who knowingly seeks to enter a region targeted by such an attack will hesitate and go to ground \endash  \i even if the attack does not succeed\i0 . The only way to stifle this primal terror is by voluntarily sacrificing 1 SAN.\par
The types of attacks which might be ruled Terror-Inducing include:\par
\pard\fi-360\li720\sa200\sl276\slmult1\f2\'b7\tab\f1 Attacks (mundane or supernatural) that inflict Lethal Damage to a Kill Zone,\par
\f2\'b7\tab\f1 Attacks which have previously been witnessed to inflict Unnatural effects worthy of a SAN test,\par
\f2\'b7\tab\f1 Anything else the GM believes would strike extreme fear into combatants.\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1 Note that these effects do not apply to a combatant who is not aware that he or she is straying into an area targeted by the Terror-Inducing attack \endash  when in doubt, call for an \b Alertness\b0  test.\par
\pard A character adapted to violence (see \b ADAPTING TO SAN LOSS\b0  on page \lang3081 74\lang1033 ) loses no SAN for braving a Terror-Inducing attack. For NPCs, it\rquote s easiest to assume the average human goes to ground when faced with such attacks. Only insane, hardened, or fanatical enemies stand up to such intense fear.\par
