\clbrdrl\brdrw10\brdrs\clbrdrt\brdrw10\brdrs\clbrdrr\brdrw10\brdrs\clbrdrb\brdrw10\brdrs \cellx10687\pard\intbl\sa200\sl276\slmult1 Normally, mundane ranged weapons won\rquote t be damaging enough to inspire terror. What if several combatants team up to concentrate simultaneous shots \endash  none of which themselves are Terror-Inducing \endash  on a single point? In such a case the GM might decide that the combined effect is sufficient to create 1 yard-radius circular zone centered on the point of concentrated fire. All combatants firing at the spot make an attack roll \endash  if the majority succeed, no damage is inflicted but the designated zone is treated as Terror-Inducing. If one or more of the attackers scored a critical on their roll, a random target in the zone is hit for normal damage \i and\i0  everyone else in the zone is affected by the Terror effect. If fewer than half of the attackers succeeded on their rolls, no damage is inflicted \i and\i0  no terror is generated.\par
\pard\intbl\sl276\slmult1 As a rule of thumb, for a concentration of smaller attacks to be ruled as creating a Terror-Inducing effect the sum of their individual maximum damages should be at least 30HP (i.e., three attacks each delivering 1D10 or five attacks each delivering 1D6). Any coordination of two or more attacks with Lethal effects would also qualify.\cell\row\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s2\fi-576\li576\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0\fs26 4.9\tab Protection in Combat\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\b0\f1\fs22 We\rquote ve seen how to injure, kill, and dismember targets, but how do you protect them?\par
There are five stages of protection, categories that determine how easy a Protagonist or other creature is to harm, regardless of their ability to get out of the way.\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s3\fi-720\li720\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0 4.9.1\tab Fragile\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\b0\i\f1 Fragile \i0 targets drop to 0 HP instantly if they suffer \i any \i0 damage from a deliberate attempt to injure them. A helpless human is Fragile and may, at the Game Moderator\rquote s discretion, be reduced to 0 HP with one attack without bothering to roll damage.\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s3\fi-720\li720\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0 4.9.2\tab Exposed\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\b0\i\f1 Exposed \i0 is the default for humans and many creatures. It means the target is aware of danger and trying to avoid it, but doesn\rquote t have any real protection. Attacks operate normally against Exposed targets.\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s3\fi-720\li720\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0 4.9.3\tab Armored\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\b0\f1 Being \i Armored \i0 reduces the damage of attacks. Armor has an Armor rating which reduces the HP damage of attacks. Armor 5 means reduce damage by 5.\par
Armor comes in two forms: \i body armor \i0 and \i cover\i0 . They both reduce the damage of ordinary attacks, but have different effects on Lethality attacks. If you have more than one source of armor (such as wearing body armor while behind a wall), add them all together.\par
\pard Some weapons are armor piercing, which in turn reduces armor (see \b ARMOR PIERCING WEAPONS\b0 , page \lang3081 54\lang1033 ). Furthermore, damage arising from wholly supernatural effects (e.g., mystical energy or psychic attacks by Mythos entities, or damage generated through rituals) completely ignores all armor. In cases where it isn\rquote t clear whether traditional armor should protect against damage dealt through otherworldly means, it is the GM\rquote s call.\par
\b BODY ARMOR:\b0  Body armor reduces the damage of an ordinary attack by its Armor Rating. Body armor protects against the damage of a failed Lethality roll, but does nothing whatsoever against a \i successful \i0 Lethality roll.\par
\b COVER:\b0  Finding cover means using a hard barrier as armor against attack. Cover protects more completely than body armor. If you have cover against a Lethality attack, the Lethality roll automatically fails, but still inflicts the sum of the dice as damage. Subtract the cover\rquote s Armor rating from that damage.\par
What if your Protagonists are completely enclosed in a structure or conveyance? That\rquote s definitely cover, but it\rquote s the Game Moderator\rquote s call. Maybe they take damage reduced by the cover, or maybe they take no damage until the cover is breached.\par
Being behind cover does not make Protagonists immune to the terror of combat (see \b FEAR IN COMBAT\b0  on page \lang3081 52\lang1033 ). If your Protagonist is terrorized, his or her next action must be to hide behind that cover instead of attacking.\par
