\pard\keep\keepn\s3\fi-720\li720\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0 4.9.6\tab Armor Piercing Weapons\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\b0\f1 An armor piercing weapon reduces the Armor value of a target by a number of points. If the weapon description notes it as armor-piercing it will normally also specify the reduction \endash  if no number is given, assume the attack reduces effective armor by 5.\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s2\fi-576\li576\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0\fs26 4.10\tab Optional Spot Rules for Weapons\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\b0\f1\fs22 There\rquote s a staggering variety of personal firearms and weaponry. Their usefulness in adventures may be limited, of course, depending on who or what the Protagonists face.\par
\pard The primary game statistics relating to different types of weapons may be found on the Example Weapons Table on page \lang3081 49\lang1033 . The availability of any class of weapon will be dictated by the scarcity of weapon resources in the particular game setting (see preceding section). \par
What follows are some spot rules for Protagonists who have access to common Jazz Age (early 20\super th\nosupersub  Century) weapons. \par
\pard\keep\keepn\s3\fi-720\li720\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0 4.10.1\tab Concealing Weapons\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\b0\f1 Knives and pistols can be concealed under ordinary clothing. Someone deliberately looking for a concealed weapon can attempt an \b Alertness\b0  test to spot it. A heavy pistol or especially big knife means a +20% Alertness bonus.\par
If a Protagonist is wearing an overcoat or trench coat, he or she can attempt to conceal a bigger gun like a sawed-off shotgun, or a larger hand weapon (e.g., a hatchet or machete) and incur no Alertness bonus.\par
There\rquote s no way to conceal a full-size rifle or a large melee weapon.\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s3\fi-720\li720\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0 4.10.2\tab Hand-to-Hand Weapons\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\b0\f1 Unarmed attacks, like punching, kicking, and strangling, use the \b Unarmed\b0  Combat skill. All melee weapons use the \b Melee Weapons\b0  skill.\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s3\fi-720\li720\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0 4.10.3\tab Primitive Ranged Weapons\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\b0\f1 Old-fashioned ranged weapons that are aimed (e.g., crossbows, bow, and slings) use the \b Firearms\b0  skill even though they aren\rquote t firearms. All such weapons require some kind of ammunition (arrows, bolts, bow) and are useless if the supply is exhausted. Primitive weapons that are thrown (e.g., spears) use \b Athletics\b0  skill.\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s3\fi-720\li720\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0 4.10.4\tab Firearms\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\b0\f1 Depending on when and where the game is set, the Protagonists may have easy access to a range of different firearms.\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s4\sb40\sl276\slmult1\cf1\i\f0 Pistols\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\i0\f1 Lightweight pistols fire low-powered cartridges and are of limited use even against humans. Medium pistols are the standard sidearms in the military everywhere. They fire moderately powerful rounds. Most revolvers hold six shots, but some late models hold seven or eight. Pocket revolvers sometimes take only five. There\rquote s a huge variety of ammunition capacities for semiautomatic pistol magazines, but 15 is typical, although 17 or even 20 is not uncommon. Large-caliber pistols often carry less. A typical figure for a heavy pistol is eight.\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s4\sb40\sl276\slmult1\cf1\i\f0 Shotguns\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\i0\f1 A typical pump-action shotgun holds five shots, although there are many with extended magazines for eight or more. Double-barrel shotguns hold one shot per barrel and can fire both barrels at one target with one attack roll. Shotguns can fire shot (a spread of small projectiles), slugs (a single heavy bullet), or \ldblquote non-lethal\rdblquote  ammunition such as salt-loaded cartridges.\par
\pard\b FIRING SHOT:\b0  Grants a +20% bonus to hit at all ranges: at point-blank due to the target being so close (see \b ATTACK MODIFIERS\b0  on page \lang3081 46\lang1033 ) and beyond that due to the spread of projectiles. If the target has an Armor rating due to armor or cover, double it.\par
\b FIRING BOTH BARRELS:\b0  You can fire both barrels of a double-barrel shotgun at one target with one attack roll. That inflicts an extra +1D8 damage at base range. It adds no damage beyond base range as the shot or the slugs separate.\par
\b OTHER GAUGES:\b0  These rules assume a standard 12-gauge (called 12-bore in England) shotgun. Modify the damage by +2 for a heavier bore or \u8722?2 for a lighter gauge.\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s4\sb40\sl276\slmult1\cf1\i\f0 Tommy Guns\par
\pard\cf0\i0\f1 Thompson submachine guns (nicknamed \ldblquote Trench brooms\rdblquote  and \ldblquote Chicago Typewriters\rdblquote ) fire full-automatic bursts but are often also capable of semi-automatic fire. When firing semi-automatic, the weapon inflicts ordinary damage; with automatic fire, it uses a Lethality rating (see \b LETHALITY RATING\b0  on page \lang3081 49\lang1033 ).\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s4\sb40\sl276\slmult1\cf1\i\f0 Rifles and Carbines\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\i0\f1 Rifles fire more powerful cartridges than pistols, for better penetration, wounding, and range. However, they are also bulkier. \par
Rifles in the Jazz Age are mostly breach loading, bolt-action weapons. These must be manually worked before each shot, which delays aiming. An attack using such a weapon in the turn immediately after it\rquote s already been fired is at \u8722?20%. A rifle gets no benefit from the \b Aim\b0  action in the turn immediately after it\rquote s fired.\par
