\b EXPRESS BULLETS (HOLLOW POINT):\b0  Late in the 19\super th\nosupersub  Century these bullets were marketed as cartridges that were lighter weight \endash  since they were hollow at the tip \endash  thereby increasing velocity. They also proved to cause greater tissue trauma, albeit at the expense of penetration. An Express (hollow point) bullet does +1 damage but armor is twice as effective against it. Express bullets were originally designed for rifles, but were also produced for larger-caliber pistols.\cell\row\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s3\fi-720\li720\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0 4.10.5\tab WW1 Machineguns & Artillery\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\b0\f1 Many unnatural things that Protagonists face are inscrutable perversions of physics no more vulnerable to explosions than they are to crucifixes. This never stops Protagonists from trying.\par
The Base Range for WW1 Machineguns reflects the fact that it needs to be accurate enough only to get a target within the Kill Radius. Such weapons fired off their tripod mounts halve Base Range.\par
Naval Guns and Field Guns are specialized pieces of equipment that require some form of Military Training at 40%+ to operate in a moderately safe fashion. They also require the concerted work of a whole team of trained military personnel. The specific skill tests needed to accurately target a Mythos horror with one of these weapons should be determined by the GM based on the specific situation. Conceivably a hit by a shell launched by a large bore gun could deal Lethality 25% across a Kill Zone of 8 yards radius. A fumble or misfire could be just as devastating to the team operating the weapon.\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s3\fi-720\li720\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0 4.10.6\tab Weapons with Special Effects\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\b0\f1 Some types of weapons do something other than (or as well as) inflicting damage to Hit Points.\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s4\sb40\sl276\slmult1\cf1\i\f0 Mustard Gas and Phosgene Gas\par
\pard\cf0\i0\f1 These terrifying forms of chemical warfare were commonly used by both sides in World War 1. Exposure to such gas creates horrific damage that is best dealt with as a form of poisoning. See the table on page \lang3081 57\lang1033 . Military gas masks are an effective, if bulky, defense but anyone wearing such a mask suffers a \u8722?20% penalty to \b Alertness\b0  and \b Search\b0  tests.\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s2\fi-576\li576\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0\fs26 4.11\tab Other Threats\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\b0\f1\fs22 The world is full of threats, combat isn\rquote t the only thing that can kill a Protagonist.\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s3\fi-720\li720\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0 4.11.1\tab Poison and Disease\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\b0\f1 Every poison or disease has two ratings: \i Speed \i0 and \i Damage\i0 .\par
\i Speed \i0 indicates how soon the poison or disease inflicts damage. A poison inflicts damage once and then passes from your Protagonist\rquote s system. A disease requires a series of CON tests to resist damage.\par
\i Damage \i0 is ordinary HP for a disease, while poisons have Lethality ratings.\par
\b POISONS:\b0  A poison has a Lethality rating. If the Lethality roll fails, the victim makes a CON\'d75 test to withstand harm. Success means half damage, and a critical success means the victim loses only 1 HP. A fumble doubles the damage. \lquote Hospitalization\rquote  (makeshift or otherwise) grants +20% to the victim\rquote s CON test.\par
