\pard\cf0\b0\f1\fs22 Each vehicle counts as a Huge target (see \b HUGE\b0 , page \lang3081 54\lang1033 ). It takes damage from unarmed attacks and small weapons such as knives and clubs only when the Game Moderator thinks it makes sense.\par
A vehicle that loses \b half\b0  its Hit Points is badly damaged. It can\rquote t be operated without a relevant skill test (depending on the type of vehicle). The next time such a test \i fumbles\i0 , the vehicle fails altogether until repaired. Repairing a damaged vehicle requires time, parts, and successful application of one or more skill tests. Even if repaired, the vehicle might now qualify as \lquote heavily worn\rquote  or \lquote junk\rquote  (see \b\caps Pre-Loved Items and Spoiled Goods\b0\caps0 , page \lang3081 61\lang1033 ).\par
A vehicle that loses \i all\i0  of its Hit Points is demolished. It will never function again.\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s3\fi-720\li720\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0 6.1.1\tab Speed\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\b0\f1 There are two broad categories of vehicle speed: Surface and Air. Any vehicle with an Air Speed rating can automatically outrun a vehicle with a Surface Speed rating (except for Hot Air Balloons, which can\rquote t outrun any vehicle, and Zeppelins which are considered equivalent speed to a Slow Surface vehicle).\par
Within the same vehicle category, some are faster than others. A vehicle with a \lquote Fast\rquote  rating grants a +20% bonus to any \b Drive\b0  or \b Pilot\b0  test to pursue or escape. A \lquote Slow\rquote  vehicle incurs a \u8722?20% penalty instead. An \lquote Average\rquote  rating confers no modifier.\par
A vehicle that\rquote s notorious for poor handling or that\rquote s in bad shape might counts as \lquote heavily worn\rquote  or \lquote junk\rquote  (see above) at the GM\rquote s discretion.\par
