Taking a powerful sedative (e.g., a barbiturate like veronal) gives your Protagonist a +20% bonus to resist an acute episode of a disorder at the cost of a \u8722?20% penalty to everything else. Using such drugs frequently makes addiction to them a likely result of your Protagonist\rquote s next disorder. If that happens, the drugs no longer confer any bonus to reduce acute episodes of a disorder, but still inflict the penalty.\par
Heavy drinking (where alcohol is available), psychedelics or cannabis gives your Protagonist a +10% bonus to resist an acute episode at the same \u8722?20% penalty to other actions. Alcohol runs the risk of addiction.\cell\row\pard\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s3\fi-720\li720\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0 7.7.2\tab Sample Disorders \par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\b0\f1 There are many adaptations the mind makes when exposed to traumatic events, whether they be violence and gore, feelings of utter helplessness, or the inherent \lquote wrongness\rquote  of unnatural Cthulhu Mythos beings. The specific disorder received by a Protagonist should never be a random roll on a table, but something specifically selected to relate to the trauma they suffered.\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s4\sb40\sl276\slmult1\cf1\i\f0 Addiction (e.g., Alcoholism, Cocainism, Morphinism)\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\i0\f1 Your Protagonist relies on a harmful habit or substance to get by. However much harm the addiction causes, your Protagonist needs the relief it offers. Losing 2+ SAN in any single roll triggers an acute episode, an overwhelming need. Feeding it usually imparts a \u8722?20% penalty to stats and skills for a few hours due to intoxication or distraction. And even in the best of times, going 24 hours without feeding the addiction costs 1D6 WP and prevents your Protagonist from recovering any WP. Every further 24 hours costs 1D6 WP. At 2 or fewer WP, your Protagonist does irrational, self-destructive things to feed the addiction.\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s4\sb40\sl276\slmult1\cf1\i\f0 Amnesia\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\i0\f1 This is a common disorder from encounters with the unnatural. Losing 2+ SAN in any single roll triggers an acute episode, which erases all memory of the episode until your Protagonist finds a way to bring it back.\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s4\sb40\sl276\slmult1\cf1\i\f0 Hysterical Condition of Blindness / Deafness / Paralysis\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\i0\f1 Collectively called conversion disorder, this can manifest either as non\u8208?physical blindness, deafness, or paralysis (pick one). Losing 2+ SAN in any single roll triggers an acute episode, which leaves your Protagonist blind, deaf, or paralyzed with numbness and tremors until the source of stress goes away.\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s4\sb40\sl276\slmult1\cf1\i\f0 Mania\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\i0\f1 Your Protagonist displays a euphoric and perhaps irritable mood that is consistently present. This may include frenzied activity for no obvious reason, uncharacteristic garrulousness, a random stream\u8208?of\u8208?consciousness flow of ideas, or difficulty sleeping. An acute episode is triggered whenever your Protagonist loses 2+ SAN in a single roll. During an acute episode all tasks which require concentration or fine control are at \b one\u8208?fifth chance.\b0\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s4\sb40\sl276\slmult1\cf1\i\f0 Megalomania / Narcissistic\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\i0\f1 What does it mean to look upon the face of a dead god and live? Some see themselves as messiahs, or as exempt from ordinary morality. Losing 2+ SAN in any single roll triggers an acute episode, in which every hint of doubt about your Protagonist\rquote s superiority fills him or her with indignation. That causes every use of a stat or skill to get help or make a good impression to fail.\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s4\sb40\sl276\slmult1\cf1\i\f0 Melancholia\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\i0\f1 Acute melancholia means total despair and a crushing inability to get anything done. It sometimes takes the shape of overwhelming guilt. An acute episode is triggered by reminders of past traumas your Protagonist suffered or inflicted, which can come in the most surprising forms and moments. During an acute episode, every skill or stat test costs 1D4 WP.\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s4\sb40\sl276\slmult1\cf1\i\f0 Multiplex Personalities\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\i0\f1 Most of the time, your Protagonist seems fine. Suffering temporary insanity or reaching the Breaking Point triggers an acute episode, in which your Protagonist takes on an alternate identity with its own personality and memories. Over time, more identities may surface. The Game Moderator decides when and whether you keep control of your Protagonist\rquote s behavior.\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s4\sb40\sl276\slmult1\cf1\i\f0 Obsession / Monomania\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\i0\f1 Your Protagonist becomes fixated on some person, place, event, act, or idea. Losing 2+ SAN in any single roll triggers an acute episode, which lasts days. In that time, any long-term action or skill use\emdash anything taking more than a few hours\emdash is at \u8722?20% because your Protagonist\rquote s mind is so often wrapped around its obsession.\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s4\sb40\sl276\slmult1\cf1\i\f0 Paranoia\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\i0\f1 A delusional state of \i Dementia Praecox\i0  (disrupted cognitive function) commonly presenting as extreme suspicion, in which a fear of invisible enemies pervades one\rquote s world-view. Losing 2+ SAN in any single roll triggers an acute episode. Unless your Protagonist finds a way to stifle his or her delusions, he or she can\rquote t trust or rely on anyone. Every event, every disagreement or source of suspicion is a clue to a conspiracy against the Protagonist.\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s4\sb40\sl276\slmult1\cf1\i\f0 Phobia or Philia\par
\pard\cf0\i0\f1 A common affliction arising from traumatic experiences is the development of an irrational fear of something related (directly or by association) with the incident. These are called phobias and can be quite debilitating. Whenever a Protagonist is in the presence of a trigger for his or her phobia, he or she must make a \b SAN\b0  test (even if the trigger is not terrifying in any way to others). Failure means an acute episode has been triggered, during which there\rquote s little choice but to suffer the Flee or Submit response to temporary insanity (see page \lang3081 69\lang1033 ). A nearby box provides some examples of phobias; searching online will reveal a huge array of other (sometimes quite weird) phobias.\par
A less common response to experiencing something shocking is the development of an irrational fetish or allure for something odd that is associated with the situation (perhaps which somehow related to the Protagonist\rquote s survival). These are called philias and work in a similar way to phobias in that whenever the afflicted Protagonist is in the presence of his or her irrational fetish a \b SAN\b0  roll is required to maintain any degree of self\u8208?control.\lang3081  \lang1033 If failed, an acute episode results during which the Game Moderator will dictate your Protagonist\rquote s actions until he or she regains control.  The list of phobias shown nearby can be converted into philias by simply inverting them: for example, where scotophobia is a fear of darkness, scotophilia is an obsessive and irrational predisposition to shroud oneself in darkness.\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s4\sb40\sl276\slmult1\cf1\i\f0 Psychogenic Fugue\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\i0\f1 Your Protagonist may shut down into catatonia or wander off in an unconnected daze. It often manifests in the face of emotional or personal complications. Suffering temporary insanity or reaching the Breaking Point triggers an acute episode during which your Protagonist may disappear for days at a time, returning with no memory of his or her recent past.\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s4\sb40\sl276\slmult1\cf1\i\f0 Schizoid\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\i0\f1 Your Protagonist\rquote s personality changes towards an uncharacteristic emotionlessness. He or she will be perceived as cold or aloof by most people. This can have a devastating effect on interpersonal relationships. In game terms, all personal interaction skill tests or \b CHA\b0  tests are halved at any time. Whenever your Protagonist loses 2+ SAN on any single roll, he or she suffers an acute episode during which the emotionlessness amplifies to the point where CHA tests must be made at \b one\u8208?fifth\b0  chance. Such episodes usually last a few days.\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s4\sb40\sl276\slmult1\cf1\i\f0 Shellshock\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\i0\f1 A common diagnosis for individuals who have encountered extraordinarily traumatic condition in the trenches of the Great War (being shelled), although it may equally well arise from other exposures to exceptionally stressful situations where a terribly traumatic encounter leaves its scars upon someone. If afflicted by \ldblquote shellshock\rdblquote  your Protagonist is frequently haunted by glimpses of traumatic events he or she witnessed in the past \endash  these create anxiety and make it hard to achieve restful sleep. An acute episode is triggered by reminders of past traumas your Protagonist suffered or inflicted. In an acute episode, the Game Moderator chooses one effect: your Protagonist either reacts violently to threats only the Protagonist perceives, or suffers an acute depressive episode. (See \b MELANCHOLIA\b0  nearby for details.)\par
