\pard\keep\keepn\s2\fi-576\li576\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0\fs26 7.8\tab Permanent Insanity\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\b0\f1\fs22 A Protagonist who drops to 0 SAN is effectively \lquote lost.\rquote  Just as being reduced to 0 Hit Points permanently removes your Protagonist from your control through physical death, being reduced to 0 SAN permanently removes your Protagonist from your control through insanity. Protagonists at 0 SAN have embraced a world of violence, helplessness, and death. No therapy or treatment will ever bring them back.\par
It remains up to the Game Moderator to determine when the Protagonist is \lquote removed\rquote  from play. Sometimes it is instant; after the SAN loss, the Protagonist collapses weeping and refuses to re-engage with reality.\par
\pard Sometimes it\rquote s more subtle. Many dangerous psychopaths get by for months or years without detection. A player who enjoys this kind of challenge may work in tandem with the Game Moderator to keep playing a character with 0 SAN as if things were normal. If you keep all SAN totals secret (see \b OPTIONAL RULE: KEEP SAN SECRET\b0\fs16  \fs22 on page \lang3081 66\lang1033 ), this should not be difficult.\par
Usually, a character who reaches 0 SAN is either \i Catatonic\i0 , \i Delusional\i0 , or \i Psychopathic\i0 .\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s4\sb40\sl276\slmult1\cf1\i\f0 Catatonia\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\i0\f1 Catatonia is complete separation. Your Protagonist\rquote s mind refuses to engage with the world that injured it. Your Protagonist no longer speaks, or eats (without prompting), or looks after him or herself; your Protagonist stares into space in a trance. Some catatonics go so deep they no longer react to physical pain. Others rise in and out of consciousness.\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s4\sb40\sl276\slmult1\cf1\i\f0 Delusions\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\i0\f1 Your Protagonist is raving, incapable of holding a conversation that does not stray into insanity. Your Protagonist is absolutely certain of the truth of his or her delusions and acts and responds as though they are completely real, even if that means violence. Nothing can dissuade your Protagonist of their reality.\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s4\sb40\sl276\slmult1\cf1\i\f0 Psychopathy\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\i0\f1 This goes beyond ordinary sociopathy. At 0 SAN, empathy has been burned out of your Protagonist. The feelings and needs of others cannot touch him or her. People are mere objects for his or her amusement or use. Your Protagonist sometimes engages in appallingly merciless actions for gratification. Some psychopaths with 0 SAN appear fine; they are no longer emotionally functional or concerned with people on a human scale, but they keep a simulated veneer of civility. Many serial killers have been classified as functional psychopaths.\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s2\fi-576\li576\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0\fs26 7.9\tab Resisting Insanity\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\b0\f1\fs22 It\rquote s possible to resist SAN loss and insanity through adaptation and by placing stress on Individual and Community Bonds. But suffering a trauma always comes with a cost.\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s3\fi-720\li720\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0 7.9.1\tab Adapting to SAN Loss\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\b0\f1 People can become hardened to traumatic stimuli. What sends one Protagonist fleeing may seem mundane to an individual who has survived it often enough. Adaptation to Violence or to Helplessness means you always succeed at a Sanity roll for that type of trauma.\par
Adaptation to Violence or adaptation to Helplessness occurs after your Protagonist has lost SAN from that kind of trauma three times in a row \i without\i0  going temporarily insane from it or hitting the Breaking Point. The character sheet has spaces to mark your Protagonist\rquote s progress toward adaptation. Each time Violence or Helplessness reduces your Protagonist\rquote s SAN by 1 or more, mark a box on your character sheet to keep track of it. \par
If your Protagonist suffers insanity from Violence \i before\i0  all three boxes are marked, erase all the \ldblquote Violence\rdblquote  boxes and start again. If your Protagonist suffers insanity from Helplessness before all three boxes are marked, erase all the \ldblquote Helplessness\rdblquote  boxes and start again. If you fill in all three boxes for Violence or all three for Helplessness, your Protagonist becomes adapted to that type of stressor.\par
\b ADAPTING TO VIOLENCE:\b0  Unfortunately, being adapted to Violence means your Protagonist\rquote s empathy suffers. He or she permanently loses 1D6 CHA and the same amount from each Bond (Individual and Community).\par
\b ADAPTING TO HELPLESSNESS:\b0  Being adapted to Helplessness means your Protagonist\rquote s personal drive suffers. As soon as your Protagonist becomes adapted to Helplessness, he or she permanently loses 1D6 POW.\par
\b ADAPTING TO THE UNNATURAL:\b0  There is no adapting to the unnatural. Things that exist beyond human comprehension are beyond \lquote getting used to.\rquote  Every new encounter is a fresh shock. The only way to \lquote adapt\rquote  to the Unnatural is to reach 0 SAN, whereupon the horrors of the Cthulhu Mythos make perfect sense and no longer inflict mental damage.\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s3\fi-720\li720\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0 7.9.2\tab Projecting Onto A Bond\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\b0\f1 When your Protagonist loses SAN, you may spend WP to reduce the loss. The amount is always 1D4: roll the die and reduce your WP by that much. \par
If your Protagonist still has at least 1 WP, reduce the SAN loss by the amount of WP spent \emdash  the amount you rolled \emdash  to a minimum of zero.\par
Now reduce one of your Protagonist\rquote s Bond scores by the \b same\b0  amount. It could be an Individual Bond or a Community Bond. The next time your Protagonist interacts with the subject of the Bond, decide what shape the projection takes. Does the Protagonist grow hostile and angry, irrationally blaming his or her loved one for imagined wrongs? Does the Protagonist abandon his community in favor of relationships with less importance and meaning? The stresses faced by Protagonists often wreck the families, friendships and associations that give them strength.\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s3\fi-720\li720\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0 7.9.3\tab Using Bonds to Repress Insanity\par
\pard\sa120\sl276\slmult1\cf0\b0\f1 Sometimes it\rquote s easier to cope with mental trauma if you pull strength and motivation from the relationships that give life meaning. You may attempt to repress the blind panic of temporary insanity or an acute episode of a disorder by spending Willpower Points. The amount is always 1D4: roll the die and reduce your WP by that much.\par
If your Protagonist still has at least 1 WP after spending the 1D4, describe how a Bond might help your Protagonist keep it together and reduce the Bond by the same amount. \par
Now attempt a SAN roll. If it succeeds, your Protagonist suppresses the insanity or disorder and behaves normally. If it fails, the attempt to repress the effects did not succeed \endash  they occur as normal, despite the points of WP and Bond strength sacrificed in the attempt.\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1 Either way, make a note to describe later how the Bond has strained because your Protagonist has taken so much support from it.\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s2\fi-576\li576\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0\fs26 7.10\tab Recovering Sanity\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\b0\f1\fs22 There are a few ways to restore mental health. These are described below.\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s3\fi-720\li720\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0 7.10.1\tab Defeating Unnatural Creatures\par
\pard\sa120\sl276\slmult1\cf0\b0\f1 The Unnatural in \i Cthulhu Eternal\i0  represents such an affront to the human mind that gaining any control over it is a sort of victory. At the Game Moderator\rquote s discretion, any destruction of a Cthulhu Mythos infiltration by a Protagonist can restore hope \emdash  and in the process, SAN.\par
As a rule, destroying an unnatural creature or an object known to contain otherworldly power restores an amount of SAN equivalent to the lowest amount that could be lost for encountering it.\par
If the SAN loss is 1/1D6, for example, destroying it restores 1 SAN. If the SAN loss is 1D6/1D20, your Protagonist gains 1D6 SAN for destroying it.\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1 This can mean your Protagonist gains more SAN from overcoming the threat than he or she actually lost from facing it. But it can never bring SAN higher than the \b Maximum SAN\b0  score: i.e., 99 minus your Protagonist\rquote s rating in the Unnatural skill.\par
Each Protagonist who was directly involved in putting the threat down gains this SAN increase.\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s3\fi-720\li720\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0 7.10.2\tab Concluding a Dangerous Adventure\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\b0\f1 Once a deadly adventure has been successfully brought to a close, all Protagonists left alive can breathe a sigh of relief that \endash  for now at least \endash  the world is a safer place. The Game Moderator is justified in awarding such Protagonists a small increase in SAN (and published scenarios may include specific SAN rewards associated with different levels of success). Such gains can never push the Protagonist\rquote s current SAN any higher than \b Maximum SAN\b0  (99 \endash  Unnatural).\par
\pard\keep\keepn\s3\fi-720\li720\sb200\sl276\slmult1\cf2\b\f0 7.10.3\tab Destroying Accounts of the Unnatural\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf0\b0\f1 To a Protagonist whose sanity has been blasted by revelations about the horrors of the Unnatural, the fact that accounts exist which lay bare such secrets is disturbing. It is via such dire accounts \endash  \lang3081 ancient tomes, journals or miscellaneous manuscripts\lang1033  \endash  that the madness spreads. Accordingly, some who have lost sanity from unnatural Mythos encounters make it their mission to track down such records and destroy them. What better way to protect humanity than rid it of these dangerous traps? This, in part, explains why true permanent accounts of the Unnatural are so rare.\par
\pard Protagonists who have experienced the Unnatural and who \i deliberately\i0  destroy a permanent record of secret information can earn a small boost to SAN, at the discretion of the Game Moderator. To qualify, the item in question must contain an actual authentic account of the Mythos (see page \lang3081 81\lang1033 ) and the Protagonist\rquote s actions must be deliberate, willful, and cause its permanent and total destruction. The Protagonist must also believe in the veracity of the account. \par
The amount of SAN increase depends upon the how many Mythos secrets the account reveals \endash  this is measured by the Unnatural skill point gain associated with reading/viewing the account.\par
